Question: Mr. Jackson’s fourth-grade class has 27 students. He wants to give each student 2 glue sticks. The glue sticks come in packs of 8. How many packs will Mr. Jackson need to buy so every student can have 2 glue sticks, assuming he can only buy whole packs and he expects to have some extra glue sticks left over?
--------------------------------------------------
Generation:

To determine how many packs of glue sticks Mr. Jackson needs to buy, we first need to calculate the total number of glue sticks required. Since each of the 27 students will receive 2 glue sticks, we multiply number of students by number of glue sticks per student:
\[ 27 \times 2 = 54 \]

Next, we need to determine how many packs of 8 are required to get at least 54 glue sticks. We do this by dividing the total number of glue sticks needed by the number of glue sticks per pack:
\[ \frac{54}{8} = 6.75 \]

Since Mr. Jackson can only buy whole packs, he needs to round up to the next whole number. Therefore, he needs to buy 7 packs of glue sticks.

