Question: Mr. Jackson’s fourth-grade class has 27 students. He wants to give each student 2 glue sticks. The glue sticks come in packs of 8. How many packs will Mr. Jackson need to buy so every student can have 2 glue sticks, assuming he can only buy whole packs and he expects to have some extra glue sticks left over?
--------------------------------------------------
Generation:

To determine how many packs of glue sticks Mr. Jackson needs to buy, we first need to calculate the total number sticks required. Since each of the 27 students will receive 2 glue sticks, we multiply the number of students by the number of glue sticks per student:

\[ 27 \times 2 = 54 \, \text{glue sticks} \]

Next, we need to determine how many packs of glue sticks are required. Each pack contains 8 glue sticks, so we divide the total number of glue sticks needed by the number of glue sticks per pack:

\[ \frac{54}{8} = 6.75 \]

Since Mr. Jackson can only buy whole packs, we need to round up to the next whole number. This is because even if he has a fraction of a pack, he will still need an additional pack to ensure he has enough glue sticks for Therefore, we round 6.75 up to 7.

Thus, Mr. Jackson needs to buy 7 packs of glue sticks to ensure everyone has 2 glue sticks.
</reasoning>

