Question: John drives for 3 hours at a speed of 60 mph and then turns around because he realizes he forgot something very important at home.  He tries to get home in 4 hours but spends the first 2 hours in standstill traffic.  He spends the next half-hour driving at a speed of 30mph, before being able to drive the remaining time of the 4 hours going at 80 mph.  How far is he from home at the end of those 4 hours?
--------------------------------------------------
Generation:

First, we calculate the distance John drives in the first 3 hours at 60 mph:
\[ 60 \text{ mph} \times 3 \text{ hours} = 180 \text{ miles} \]

Next, we calculate the distance John drives in the next half-hour at 30 mph:
\[ 30 \text{ mph} \times 0.5 \text{ hours} = 15 \text{ miles} \]

Then, we calculate the distance John drives in the remaining 1 hour at 80 mph:
\[ 80 \text{ mph} \times 1 \text{ hour} = 80 \text{ miles} \]

Adding these distances together gives us the total distance John drives:
\[ 180 \text{ miles} + 15 \text{ miles} + 80 \text{ miles} = 275 \text{ miles} \]

Since, John turns around and does home, he is 275 miles from home.
</reasoning>
<answer>
\boxed{275}
</answer><|eot_id|><|endoftext|>
