Question: Mr. Jackson’s fourth-grade class has 27 students. He wants to give each student 2 glue sticks. The glue sticks come in packs of 8. How many packs will Mr. Jackson need to buy so every student can have 2 glue sticks, assuming he can only buy whole packs and he expects to have some extra glue sticks left over?
--------------------------------------------------
Generation:

Mr. Jackson needs to give each student 2 glue sticks, and he has 27 students. Therefore, he needs a total of $27 \times 2 = 54$ glue sticks. The glue sticks come in packs of 8, so we need to determine how many packs are required to get 54 glue sticks. We perform this calculation by dividing 54 by 8, which gives us 6 with a remainder of 6. Since Mr Jackson must buy whole packs, he will need to buy 7 packs to ensure he has enough glue sticks.
</reasoning>
<answer>
\boxed{7}
